Before we take care of others, we need to take care of ourselves. Dig into the concept of radical self-care with @lamarodofficial’s new series on Calm. 

“Many people are struggling to feel well right now,” says Lama Rod. “This series is for anyone who is interested in why they hurt—and how to transform that hurt into something that feels more balanced and connected to the experiences of others.” 

Explore the Radical Self-Care series on Calm (link in bio).

node.text:
💙 @lamarodofficial comes to Calm with a unique perspective on meditation, born from his experiences as a Black, queer male raised in the South and heavily influenced by his upbringing and the community.

In his new series, Radical Self-Care, Lama Rod shares how he disrupted harmful narratives about himself and others through meditation and self-love. “I’m a complex human being, and I bet you are, too,” says Lama Rod. “Let’s explore this complexity through meditation, and learn tools to show up for ourselves and the world around us in a way that is more honest, real, direct, and caring.”

Listen to Radical Self-Care now on Calm (link in bio).

From our team to yours, happy #EmployeeAppreciationDay! No matter where you work, we see you, we support you, and we appreciate you today and every day.

➡️ Want a new way to show your team you care? Check out Calm for Business, which partners with organizations to offer Calm as an employee benefit. Tap our bio link to learn more and share with your HR team.

node.title: A Day In The Life 💙 Calm Team

node.text: Enter a world where everything you love about our Sleep Stories comes to life on the big screen. On October 1, join us on a journey through A World of Calm, available exclusively on @hbomax.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says '9 WAYS TO Train Your Mind Calm'.

node.text:
You can train your mind to be clearer, more focused and efficient, just like you can train your body to run the 3,000m or master taekwondo. And you don’t need to be an athlete (or break a sweat) to do it. 

Thanks to mental strength training and “neuroplasticity” (the ability of the brain’s neural networks to change through growth and reorganization), anyone can rewire their mind to become stronger, healthier, and fitter than ever before. All it takes is time, practice, and consistency. 

💪🧠 To get you started, here are nine ways to train your mind. Check out the blog for more including our free Mental Fitness Training Guide. Link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says '9 WAYS TO Train Your Mind Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Meditate Meditation is one of the best ways to train your mind. It strengthens our ability to witness our thoughts, and is the first step in shifting the mental habits that cause us trouble. The key is consistency. Start small with 5 or 10 minutes of meditation a day and build up slowly. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Connect with the present moment It's easy to get lost in overthinking, but this mental pattern can be distracting, unhelpful and exhausting The trick is to catch yourself when you're ruminating and invite yourself back to the present moment Explore your senses what can you see, hear, feel, smell, and taste? Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Rest your mind No different than taking a break in between sprints or a set of deadlifts, your brain needs time to reset and recharge too. Rest increases our focus, creativity, energy, and productivity. Find an activity that you find restorative -reading, music, gardening, whatever works for you. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Minimize digital distractions We live in an age of digital distraction that can pul us away from what's important and leave us feeling overwhelmed and exhausted Try a digital clean-up, like minimizing notifications on your phone, or scheduling regular periods of technology-free time. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Prioritize sleep Sleep allows our brain (and body) to repair and recover. It also improves memory, mood, creativity, and problem-solving skills. So to show up in the world as our best selves, it's crucial that we give ourselves quality time to recharge. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Leverage your routines Routine is the key to training the mind, and we have a built-in neurological system we can activate to support us. Try adding meditation to a routine that's already in place, like after brushing your teeth. Soon enough, your toothbrush will become a mental cue for your meditation practice. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Practice letting go Trying to control our lives and the people in them is a one-way ticket to anxiety and exhaustion. Accept what you can't control, and let your best efforts be enough for now. Letting go isn't easy, it takes practice and patience, so be kind to the part of you that finds it difficult. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Tune into your intuition Training the mind involves tuning in to and trusting your instincts. It's about listening to that gut feeling and acting in alignment with your inner knowing This isn't always easy, but it's a powerful way to build a relationship of trust with ourselves. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 03, 2021. May be an image of book, sky and text that says 'Learn more in Calm's Mental Fitness Training Guide MENTAL FITNESS TRAINING GUIDE Strengthen Strengouindndiv your hrive. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on August 02, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, outdoors and text that says 'On days you can't hear yourself, slow down to let your mind and your body catch up to each other. RUPI KAUR Calm'.

node.text:
The only constant in life is change. Yet that doesn’t mean it’s easy to navigate.

Whether positive or painful, it can be tricky to adjust to changes in our lives, particularly when they feel unexpected or beyond our control.

Being able to cope better with change is about holding space for our feelings, fine-tuning our resilience, and meeting ourselves with patience as we recalibrate to our new reality. 

Here are nine ways to support yourself as you move through change. 💙🌊

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says '9 WAYS TO Navigate Change Mindfully Calm'.

Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Resist resisting Our first instinct when confronted with change is often to want to fight or resist. Allow yourself to sit with the uncertainty, no matter how uncomfortable. See if you can accept the way things are and open y”usf to the possibility of opportunity and growth. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Validate your feelings Change isn't easy. Even positive change can feel challenging. Instead of forcing yourself to react a certain way, honor the way you're feeling in each moment. Holding space for our emotions allows us to cultivate the acceptance, compassion and ease we need to navigate the swirls. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Manage your expectations It's natural to want to adapt to change quickly. But adjusting takes time. Notice whether you are expecting too much from yourself, too soon, or if you're comparing yourself to others. It's okay to take things slowly. The important thing is to pace yourself Calm'.

Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Flex your equanimity muscle Equanimity is the mind's ability to be okay with whatever is happening good, bad or ugly. It teaches us that no matter what tumbles our way, we will be okay. Practice equanimity by regularly pausing before you respond, observing your breath, tuning into your body, and meditating. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Lean into routine When we're thrown into times of change, our routines can bring us the comfort and stab we crave. Whether it's your morning cup of coffee, a familiar walk in nature, or heading to bed at the same time each night, reinforce your routines and rituals. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Reflect on your resilience Consider the big changes you've moved through in your life. Even if change hasn't felt positive to begin with, chances are that moving out of your comfort zone has been where you've learnt and grown the most. You've got through it before, you'll be okay this time too. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Prioritize self-care Change is tiring. Support your body and mind by taking extra good care of yourself. Make sure you're getting the sleep, exercise, down-time, and enjoyment you need. Don't be afraid to create or re-establish boundaries to protect your peace. It's okay to say no. Calm'.

Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Savor the good When life is shifting, it's especially important to tap into the good in your life, and to enjoy the things that bring you joy. Savoring these moments rewires your brain for happiness and builds resilience. Your senses can help. What can you see, hear, feel, smell, and taste? Calm'.

Photo by Calm on July 27, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Express yourself Feelings of anxiety, fear and overwhelm are common when we're facing change. Talk to someone who's in the same boat, share how you're feeling with a friend who's been there, or pour your worries onto the page with some journaling. Calm'.
Photo by Calm on July 26, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, outdoors and text that says 'The rest is just as important as the work. Take time to recharge. Calm'.
